The usual rules for error checking in these sorts of situations are:

1. Do check for error returns.  (You&#39;re doing that.)
2. Do print a useful error message.  (You&#39;re doing that.)
3. Print error messages to `stderr`.
4. If the error involves a file, do include the filename in the error message.
5. If the error involves a function that sets `errno`, do print the &quot;perror&quot; text&quot; (&quot;No such file or directory&quot;, etc.).
6. If you&#39;re writing a tool that will be combined into larger scripts, do include the program&#39;s name in the error message.
7. If the error occurs due to an input file you&#39;re reading, do print the name of that file and the line number.

Adopting rules 1 through 6, an improved version of your error check would be

    if(pfile == NULL) {
        fprintf(stderr, &quot;%s: can&#39;t open %s: %s\n&quot;, progname, buffer, strerror(errno));
        return EXIT_FAILURE;
    }

For this to work you&#39;ll need both of:

    #include &lt;string.h&gt;
    #include &lt;errno.h&gt;

If that&#39;s too much  work, a simpler way is just to call

    perror(buffer);

although this falls down somewhat on rules 2, 6, and 7.

